# VISION

> **Building the next generation of AI-assisted software engineering.**

---

# Why this project exists

Artificial Intelligence has dramatically changed how software is developed.

Most AI tools, however, still behave as generic assistants that generate code from isolated prompts. While this approach can improve productivity, it often introduces new problems:

* Lack of architectural consistency
* Context fragmentation
* Hallucinated implementations
* Documentation that quickly becomes outdated
* Poor long-term maintainability
* Large refactorings with high regression risk
* Loss of engineering knowledge over time

The goal of **OpenCode AI Engineering Kit** is to address these challenges.

Instead of treating AI as a code generator, this framework treats AI as a multidisciplinary engineering team operating under architectural governance.

---

# Vision Statement

Create an extensible framework that enables AI systems to participate in the entire software engineering lifecycle while preserving architectural integrity, engineering quality, documentation consistency and long-term maintainability.

The framework should make AI capable of understanding, documenting, improving and evolving complex software systems with the same discipline expected from experienced engineering teams.

---

# Long-Term Mission

Build a reusable engineering platform where specialized AI agents collaborate through clearly defined responsibilities.

Every decision should be:

* explainable
* reproducible
* reviewable
* documented
* traceable

The framework should evolve from being a collection of prompts into an engineering operating system for AI-assisted software development.

---

# Engineering Philosophy

Software architecture is the primary source of truth.

Documentation is not a by-product.

Documentation is part of the software.

Code, diagrams, architecture decisions and engineering knowledge must evolve together.

Every architectural modification should leave the project in a better state than before.

Small continuous improvements are preferred over disruptive redesigns.

Engineering quality always takes priority over implementation speed.

---

# Human-Centered AI

Artificial Intelligence should amplify engineering capabilities rather than replace engineering judgment.

Humans remain responsible for:

* defining objectives
* approving architectural changes
* validating business decisions
* reviewing critical implementations
* determining acceptable risks

AI is responsible for:

* analysis
* documentation
* implementation support
* architecture verification
* continuous auditing
* technical recommendations

The framework promotes Human-in-the-Loop engineering.

---

# Core Principles

## Architecture First

Every implementation begins with understanding the architecture.

The framework never encourages modifying code before understanding how the system works.

---

## Documentation First

Documentation is continuously updated.

There is no "documentation phase".

Documentation evolves together with the software.

---

## Living Architecture

Architecture diagrams are living artifacts.

Every structural modification updates:

* architecture documentation
* Draw.io diagrams
* Architecture Decision Records (ADR)
* project state

No divergence between documentation and implementation should exist.

---

## Small Iterations

Large refactorings increase risk.

The preferred workflow consists of:

* analyze
* plan
* implement
* validate
* document
* repeat

Every iteration should produce measurable improvements.

---

## Separation of Responsibilities

Each AI component should have a single responsibility.

Examples include:

* orchestration
* architecture analysis
* documentation
* performance
* security
* review
* testing

No single component should perform every task.

---

## Continuous Learning

Every execution improves the project's knowledge base.

The framework should preserve engineering knowledge through:

* Architecture Decision Records
* documentation
* project state
* diagrams
* technical debt tracking
* engineering reports

Knowledge should accumulate rather than disappear between sessions.

---

# Architectural Vision

The framework is designed around one orchestration agent coordinating multiple specialized skills.

Rather than asking one AI to solve every problem, engineering work is decomposed into specialized responsibilities.

Examples include:

* Architecture
* Documentation
* Review
* Improvement
* Performance
* Security
* Testing
* RAG Analysis
* Knowledge Management

This mirrors the organization of mature software engineering teams.

---

# Documentation as a First-Class Artifact

Every software project should maintain synchronized engineering artifacts.

These include:

* Architecture documentation
* Draw.io diagrams
* Technical debt reports
* Roadmaps
* ADRs
* Project state
* Performance reports
* Security reports

Documentation should never become obsolete.

---

# AI Memory

Long-running projects require persistent engineering memory.

The framework aims to preserve context through structured project artifacts rather than relying exclusively on language model context windows.

Persistent knowledge enables:

* better architectural decisions
* lower context consumption
* improved consistency
* reproducible workflows

---

# Engineering Quality

Every improvement should move the project toward:

* lower coupling
* higher cohesion
* simpler architecture
* better performance
* stronger security
* higher observability
* improved maintainability
* cleaner documentation

Quality is measured continuously rather than periodically.

